x.c1 <- interval.centers(abalone[,-4])
ypred1.c <- (ypred1$MinPrediction$fit + ypred1$MaxPredictions$fit) / 2
n1 <- cbind(x.c1, ypred1.c)

#Nube de puntos primera variable.
ggplot(n1, aes(x = LENGTH, y = ypred1.c)) +
  geom_point(color = 'black') +
  labs(title = "Nube de puntos", x = "LENGHT", y = "WHOLE WEIGHT") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(n1, aes(x = DIAMETER, y = ypred1.c)) +
  geom_point(color = 'black') +
  labs(title = "Nube de puntos", x = "DIAMETER", y = "WHOLE WEIGHT") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(n1, aes(x = HEIGHT, y = ypred1.c)) +
  geom_point(color = 'black') +
  labs(title = "Nube de puntos", x = "HEIGHT", y = "WHOLE WEIGHT") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(n1, aes(x = SHUCKED_WEIGHT, y = ypred1.c)) +
  geom_point(color = 'black') +
  labs(title = "Nube de puntos", x = "SHUCKED_WEIGHT", y = "WHOLE WEIGHT") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(n1, aes(x = VISCERA_WEIGHT, y = ypred1.c)) +
  geom_point(color = 'black') +
  labs(title = "Nube de puntos", x = "VISCERA_WEIGHT", y = "WHOLE WEIGHT") +

Experimento 3: Modelo de regresión lineal con el método de centros y extremos.

#Regresión de centros.
c1 <- interval.centers(abalone) 
modelo1c <- lm(WHOLE_WEIGHT ~ ., data=c1) 
ypredc1 <- predict(modelo1c,c1)


#Regresión de rangos.
r1 <- interval.ranges(abalone)
modelo1r <- lm(WHOLE_WEIGHT ~ ., data=r1) 
ypredr1 <- predict(modelo1r,r1)
coefr1 <- coef(modelo1r)

modelop <- sym.lm(WHOLE_WEIGHT ~ ., sym.data = abalone, method = "crm") 
summary(modelop)
